====Usage notes====
From the beginning of the 20th century, ''bathroom'' has been the generic word for a room with toilet facilities in American English<ref>[https://books.google.com/ngrams/graph?content=water+closet%2Cbathroom%2Crestroom%2CWC%2Clavatory%2Cwashroom%2Cmens+room%2Cladies+room%2Cmen%27s+room%2Cwomen%27s+room%2Cladies%27+room%2Clittle+boys+room&year_start=1800&year_end=2008&corpus=17&smoothing=3&share=&direct_url=t1%3B%2Cwater%20closet%3B%2Cc0%3B.t1%3B%2Cbathroom%3B%2Cc0%3B.t1%3B%2Crestroom%3B%2Cc0%3B.t1%3B%2CWC%3B%2Cc0%3B.t1%3B%2Clavatory%3B%2Cc0%3B.t1%3B%2Cwashroom%3B%2Cc0%3B.t1%3B%2Cmens%20room%3B%2Cc0%3B.t1%3B%2Cladies%20room%3B%2Cc0%3B.t1%3B%2Cmen%20%27s%20room%3B%2Cc0%3B.t1%3B%2Cwomen%20%27s%20room%3B%2Cc0%3B.t1%3B%2Cladies%20%27%20room%3B%2Cc0%3B.t1%3B%2Clittle%20boys%20room%3B%2Cc0 Google Ngram (American English)].</ref>.  As Britons continue to say {{m|en|lavatory}} relatively more frequently and often {{m|en|loo}} or {{m|en|WC}} for a room with a toilet but no bath. Partly from French influence, such rooms are also relatively more common in British homes.[citation needed]

In some contexts, ''bathroom'' refers more particularly to the toilet facilities of a private residence, distinguished from public buildings' {{m|en|restroom}}''s'', {{m|en|men's room}}''s'', {{m|en|ladies' room}}''s'', etc.

